Hey CD,

Our team has been using a 2 flute end mill from Yonico recently, but we want to have chips that aren‚Äôt total dust. An alumnus from our team recommended we use an O flute or single flute carbide upcut bit, and we are having some trouble finding some cheap options online. This AMANA bit has the dimensions we want, but not the price. Are there any alternatives or vendors that you have had good experiences with?

I also found these that would work.

  • Team 2658, E-Motion

bobbysq:

They don‚Äôt seem to have the 1/4 shank size you want, but I believe that can be solved with some sort of adapter for the 4mm ones, or it may be better in the long run to get additional collets for your router so you can use more sizes of bits.

It‚Äôs worth noting that collet reducers will add runout, but if OP decides to take that route my brief testing suggests spending a bit more on a brand name reducer is worth it.

I‚Äôm in the middle of building a kit CNC router myself and recently did some runout measurements between the Bosch 1617EVS router I‚Äôm planning to use as a spindle. The 1617EVS comes with both 1/4" and 1/2" collets and I measured the following runouts with a .0005" increment Shars test indicator:

  • 1/4" collet (no reducer) + 1/4" shank countersink from McMaster: ~.0005 TIR @ ~1/8" from collet nut.
  • 1/4" collet (no reducer) + 1/4" LMT Onsrud single flute endmill: ~.00025 TIR @ ~1/8" from collet nut.
  • 1/2" collet (no reducer) + random 1/2" shank countersink in my toolbox: ~.0005" TIR @ ~1/8" from collet nut
  • 1/2" collet + Amana tool 1/2" to 6 mm collet reducer + HQMaster 6 mm single flute endmill: ~.0015" TIR @ ~1/8" from collet nut.
  • 1/2" collet + uxcell 1/2" to 6 mm collet reducer + the same 6 mm endmill as above: ~.0045 TIR @ ~1/8" from collet nut.

For FRC purposes, I suspect a good quality reducer will probably be fine, and in some cases (e.g: using a hand router as a spindle) it may be the only way to use tools with otherwise unsupported shank diameters.

As for cheap bits, the only ones we use are the 4mmx4mmx12mm Huhao bits. I‚Äôm sure there are better, but at <$2/endmill we feel zero guilt about any learning mistakes or even just throwing out bits that aren‚Äôt performing well.
